column6: Postdoc at AI2; Incoming Assistant Professor at the University of Waterloo
column7:
My research interests are Natural Language Processing and Machine Learning. My research philosophy is to "build AIs for machines": since machines and humans have different characteristics, the ways humans solve problems might not necessarily be optimal for machines. For example, humans communicate using language, but there might be more effective ways of communication between machines than human language. Therefore, in the near future, I plan to study communication and cooperation among multiple models (aka agents):

- Communication among Models: I plan to learn a communication language between models that is more effective than human language (such as continuous vectors or discrete semantic representations).
- Division of labor and cooperation: Unlike the current practice of training a single all-capable large model, I plan to train a group of small specialized models with different capabilities to complete tasks through communication and cooperation.

I also work on open-source projects such as OpenNMT, Im2LaTeX, LaTeX2Im, and Steganography to make my research efforts more readily available for developers and researchers.

column6: PhD candidate studying approaches to biological network integration using deep learning.
column7:
I am a soon-to-graduate PhD student at the University of Toronto. My thesis work is to design, implement and validate a new approach to biological network integration for the purpose of identifying new subsystems of genes and proteins in the cell, thereby improving their functional characterization. I have implemented a state-of-the-art deep learning network integration algorithm called BIONIC which has been published in Nature Methods.

My interests are broad, ranging from pure machine learning research (with an emphasis on graph neural networks, neural network architecture design and reinforcement learning), to applied deep learning algorithm design and open problems in computational biology and genomics (with a focus on in silico cellular modeling). I have a strong background in mathematics and computer science as well as an appreciation for the challenges of applying machine learning models to real world data.

If you are interested in my skill set or research, please feel free to reach out!

column7: Dr. Brokoslaw Laschowski is a postdoctoral research fellow in the Temerty Faculty of Medicine at the University of Toronto working in the Intelligent Assistive Technology and Systems Laboratory. He also holds an affiliation with the Artificial Intelligence and Robotics in Rehabilitation Lab at the Toronto Rehabilitation Institute. As a research scientist, he specializes in the design and control of wearable robotic systems and technologies using a human-machine systems engineering approach. Applications of his research include rehabilitation robotics, neural engineering, human-computer interaction, and assistive technology like robotic prosthetic legs and exoskeletons. His clinical research focuses on assisting individuals with mobility impairments due to aging and/or physical disabilities such as stroke, cerebral palsy, osteoarthritis, Parkinson’s disease, amputation, and spinal cord injury. His research also includes the design and integration of sensory feedback systems (e.g., smart glasses and haptics) for persons with visual impairments. Overall, he develops technologies that interface with humans in order to improve health and performance.

column6: MScAC Student || Aspiring AI/ML Researcher || Backend Systems Engineer
column7:
In my career, as in many things, life imitates art.

Douglas Adams' sci-fi comedy "The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy" transfixed me as a kid, its plot set in motion by the near-godly supercomputer Deep Thought - the powerful machine meant to find the answer to life, the universe, and everything. (After 7.5 million years, the Answer turned out to be 42.) 

Amusing though that was, the notion stuck with me, reinforced by more works of sci-fi, of powerful computers surpassing human limits to solve problems and answer questions that wield great power to reshape the world - whether for good (Charles Babbage's titular computers of "The Difference Engine") or for evil (the Allied Mastercomputer of "I Have No Mouth and I Must Scream.") The tale of Deep Thought left a second imprint on me as well: explaining its seemingly useless answer, it added that "once you know what the Question actually is, you'll know what the Answer means." And though this was only meant to set up the book's plot, it took on new meaning as I began studying the world of machine learning - the power of clustering, PCA, and neural networks to find answers even their creators could not conceive, raising orderly patterns from disorderly data and uncovering rules where none were known to exist.

The arc of my career has led me in pursuit of those intelligent machines, building on my fascination with math and my education in computing, tackling the world's problems once thought impossibly complicated. As part of the University of Toronto's Master of Science in Applied Computing (MScAC) program, specializing in artificial intelligence, I'm aiming to secure an applied research internship to dive further into the details of this bold new space, especially in the field of robotics, creating machines capable of interacting with and changing even the physical world. 

Open to discussions on any interesting technical subjects and, should it suit you, Douglas Adams' novels. 

Remember, "DON'T PANIC!"

Nisarg Shah is an assistant professor of computer science at the University of Toronto and a Research Lead at the Schwartz Reisman Institute for Technology and Society. He has been recognized as AI's 10 to Watch by IEEE Intelligent Systems in 2020. He is also the winner of the 2016 IFAAMAS Victor Lesser Distinguished Dissertation Award and the 2014-2015 Facebook PhD Fellowship. Shah conducts research at the intersection of computer science and economics, addressing issues of fairness, efficiency, elicitation, and incentives that arise when humans are affected by algorithmic decision-making. His recent work develops theoretical foundations for fairness in fields such as voting, resource allocation, and machine learning. He has co-developed two not-for-profit websites, Spliddit.org and RoboVote.org, which have helped more than 200,000 users make provably fair and optimal decisions in their everyday lives. He earned his PhD in computer science at Carnegie Mellon University and was a postdoctoral fellow at Harvard University. 

Email: nisarg@cs.toronto.edu
Twitter: @nsrg_shah

column7: I'm a Ph.D. candidate at the Department of Computer Science, University of Toronto, supervised by Roger Grosse. Previously, I did my undergraduate at the Department of Electronic Engineering, Tsinghua University.

As a 4th-year student in Ryerson’s Medical Physics program, I have always been interested in the potential of physics to tackle interdisciplinary problems. Armed with a curious nature and participation in a wide range of experiences, I love to test myself with complex and ever evolving problems. This pursuit has led me accepting and offer to a Masters of Physics in Complex Systems this upcoming fall semester.
Over the past number of years, I worked as a software developer and as an undergraduate researcher and completed a college degree in audio engineering. My research has included studying “superspreader events” in the COVID-19 crisis, studying the universality of prediction markets, studying the impacts of youth programming on developmental outcomes, and researching how concealing network information from deep learning agents to reduce their ability to learn network weaknesses. These research experiences resulted in: interdisciplinary papers, receiving NSERC funding, and increasing my knowledge in the domains of information theory and machine learning.
This theme of expanding my skills through new experiences was a huge motivator in recording, mixing and mastering Sydanie’s “999,” which was long-listed for the Polaris Prize, recognizing excellence in Canadian music. Supporting Sydanie in relaying her empowering messages of young, black motherhood on this thesis of resistance was deeply rewarding.
All future experiences would be welcomed, so feel free to reach out and we can explore options over a cup of coffee.

column7: I'm a PhD candidate with a passion for bridging the gap between the frontiers of emerging scientific research and the actual reality of industry. I study in the modelling and computational science program at Ontario Tech University, working in Prof. Hendrick de Haan's cNAB.LAB for computational nanobiophysics. My recent research is at the interface of computational physics and deep learning, and includes: computational studies of DNA-like molecules in micro- and nanofluidic systems, investigations of representation and transfer learning in the context of scientific computing, and numerical analyses of deep learning techniques for solving differential equations in biophysics. Additionally, I have worked on computational physics research projects involving solar dynamics, dark matter detection, machine vision using cosmic rays, and advanced nuclear reactor designs. Besides my research work, I co-founded the startup Altrina AI during my PhD. The vision for this company is to deliver reliable scientific machine learning tools for industrial applications. We have explored opportunities in a variety of sectors, including automatic detection of localization of faults in power grids, detection and interpretation of underwater threats in military settings, advanced simulation and design tools for nonlinear elastic materials, and more.

column7:
My goal in research is to contribute understanding and techniques to the growing science of responsible AI development, while usefully applying AI to high-impact ecological problems including climate change, epidemiology, and ecological impact assessments. My recent research has two themes (1) using deep models for policy analysis and risk mitigation, and (2) designing data or unit test environments to empirically evaluate learning behaviour or simulate deployment of an AI system. 
I am broadly interested in studying “what goes into” deep models - not only data, but the broader learning environment including task design/specification, loss function, and regularization; as well as the broader societal context of deployment including privacy considerations, trends and incentives, norms, and human biases. I'm concerned and passionate about AI ethics, safety, and the application of ML to environmental management, health, and social welfare.

I cannot wait to see where learning will take me next!

column6: researcher with training in Theoretical Physics and a strong experience in Machine Learning
column7:
I am a PhD student at Perimeter Institute for Theoretical Physics and the University of Waterloo. My advisor is Roger Melko.
My research is on the intersection between theoretical quantum many-body physics and machine learning. I apply machine learning as a computational tool to solve problems in quantum physics, and I use approaches from theoretical physics to understand deep learning. My goal is to develop a theoretical foundation of deep learning which would in turn allow to expand its applicability in physics. I am particularly interested in approaches involving information theory, statistical learning theory, and statistical physics. Several of my recent projects on the machine-learning side focus on adversarial attacks and model robustness.
Previously, I completed the Perimeter Scholars International master's program (2017), a MSc in Theoretical Physics with focus on computational approaches to quantum many-body systems (2016), and a BSc in Biophysics (2014) at the Goethe University in Frankfurt, Germany.

column7:
Information Theory establishes the fundamental limits of machine learning, but it does not account for computational and memory constraints. My goal is to develop algorithms and theory that incorporate these resource constraints into generative modelling and data compression.

Our work on optimally compressing sets/multisets under these constraints has led to new algorithms for storing large graphs with millions of nodes and edges in feasible time (quasi-linear in the number of edges), while simultaneously outperforming current state-of-the-art ad hoc methods. As part of a coursework project, I made a fully functional application called AttendanceCam, which logs attendance of students in a classroom through facial recognition, harnessing the AI capabilities of Microsoft’s Azure platform.
It was then that I could fully comprehend the endless possibilities of Artificial Intelligence and its applications. My favourite thing about AI is that it can be combined with any other field that interests me, opening up infinite permutations about what could be made. I can’t think of any other field that can be applied so pervasively. Therefore, being an astute political observer, I decided to pursue extensive research on the methods of election prediction using Machine Learning and Data Analysis. For this, working on and implementing a variety of ML algorithms gave me a more hands-on experience.
During the past year, I have been intrigued by Deep Learning. For my final semester, I wrote a research paper that compares Computer Vision and Deep Learning techniques for lane following and sign recognition. For its experimental analysis, I had to implement these techniques on a Raspberry Pi car. For lane following, a widely used CNN architecture was compared to a purely Computer Vision based approach; while for sign recognition a classical CNN architecture was compared to more modern object detection algorithms such as YOLO, SSD, and R-CNN. It was exhilarating to see my project come to life during its implementation after reading a lot of papers.
I enjoy being challenged and love engaging with projects that require me to work outside my comfort zone and knowledge set.

Hi, I’m Chris. I’m a MASc Candidate in Systems Design Engineering at the University of Waterloo. I’m a member of the Vision and Image Processing Lab, supervised by Alexander Wong and David Clausi. I’m also affiliated with the Waterloo AI Institute and the Partnership on AI, through the VIP Lab’s membership. 
My research interests lie in the social impact of artificial intelligence. I am broadly interested in using my technical knowledge to better understand how deep learning systems operate, such that undesirable biases in these systems can be mitigated. I am specifically interested in fairness and privacy implications of face recognition technology, as this technology poses a high risk for misuse. Additionally, I am interested in data collection policies to better understand how assumptions are codified into data, and how decisions in this process may lead to representational bias in training datasets and evaluation bias in benchmark datasets.

column6: AI Researcher, with expertise in machine learning, computer vision, and physical simulations.
column7:
Micha is a machine learning researcher, focusing on latent variable models, representation learning, Bayesian inference, and semi-supervised/unsupervised learning.
He recently graduated his PhD under the supervision of prof. David Fleet in the Department of Computer Science at University of Toronto, and in the Vector Institute, Toronto.
Micha has been working on machine learning, computer vision, physical inference, and optimization problems for the better part of the last decade.
In the past, he focused mainly on 3D video tracking combined with physical models.
Currently he has been focusing on representation learning, generative models, Bayesian modelling (always go Bayesian!),
and in particular the Mutual Information Machine (MIM). MIM is trained with a new symmetric variational inference,
which learns a latent representation with high mutual information, and low marginal entropy.
Importantly, MIM is not prone to suffer from posterior collapse, unlike VAEs.
If you use VAE, you might find MIM useful! I am always looking for interesting collaborations.

column6: PhD student and Research Assistant - University of Waterloo
column7: I am currently a PhD student in the department of Electrical and Computer Engineering at the University of Waterloo, advised by professors Mark Crowley and Kate Larson. My primary research interest is in the area of multi-agent systems. I am interested in the issues of scale, non-stationarity, communication and sample complexity in multi-agent learning systems. As a consequence, my area of work is in the intersection of Reinforcement Learning and Game Theory. I am also highly interested in theoretical aspects of Reinforcement Learning. I have two important and related long term research goals. The first is to bridge the widening gap between the theoretical understanding and empirical advances of Multi-agent Reinforcement Learning.  The second is to make multi-agent learning algorithms applicable to a variety of large-scale real-world problems. Before starting a PhD, I obtained a Master’s degree in the ECE department at the University of Waterloo, supervised by professor Mark Crowley. My bachelor's degree was in the field of Geomatics Engineering, from College of Engineering Guindy, Chennai, India. During this time I completed a Mitacs funded research internship in the Spatial lab, under the supervision of Professor Colin Robertson in Wilfrid Laurier University.  I have also worked as a research intern at Borealis AI- Edmonton and Waterloo labs. In general, my research is motivated by the field of Computational Sustainability.

column7:
Dr. Xiaopu Zhou has been focusing on investigating the underlying mechanism of Alzheimer’s disease (AD). During his postgraduate study at the Hong Kong university of Science and Technology under the supervision of Prof. Nancy Ip, he has received training in biochemistry and molecular biology techniques, as well as genetics and bioinformatics. He led the first whole-genome sequencing study for AD in the Chinese population and identified AD genetic risks associated with immune pathways in the Chinese population (Zhou et.al., 2018). In addition, he demonstrated the role of non-coding AD risk in APOE nearby regions in modifying AD risk as well as APOE expression (Zhou et.al., 2019).

His recent research focuses on analyzing multi-omics data for early diagnosis and risk prediction of Alzheimer's disease and investigating its underlying pathophysiology. In particular, he has developed the first deep- learning-based polygenic risk score model for classifying AD risk based on genomic data (Zhou et.al., under review).

I am passionate about using Artificial Intelligence to create a positive impact in people's lives.

column7: An active researcher within the domain of Artificial Intelligence (AI) with respect to Social Network Analysis (SNA). My research entails harnessing Machine Learning (ML) and Deep Learning (DL) methodologies toward resolving a vast range of open (research) problems and real-world problems in SNA. To this end, I have successfully developed and implemented effective as well as efficient frameworks for resolving the following research problems, viz: Breakup Prediction, Link Prediction, Link Influence and Dynamics, Node Classification, Trend/Pattern Analysis, and Event-based Analysis/Prediction. In this regard, my research and work have been funded as well as supported by NSERC, CIHR, IBM, Vector Institute for Artificial Intelligence, etc. Also, I am a seasoned solutions and web/mobile developer with over 10 years of industry experience. I am flexible, collaborative, and a good multi-tasker who is self-motivated, committed, and target-driven. I can adapt swiftly to newer skills, and can manage time and other resources wisely without constant supervision.

column7:
Maria Khan is a bilingual content director with a solid track record in helping A-list brands develop thought leadership and make social impact. A journalist by training, Maria brings a decade of experience in producing content for print and online publications in the Middle East, UK and the US. 
Passionate about storytelling and societal issues, Maria, has contributed investigative-style stories for print and online publications in the UAE and the UK, and directed and produced several short video and audio documentaries, including a podcast on the role of ethics in Photojournalism for the Monocle24 radio in the UK.
While working for top PR agency FleishmanHillard in the UK, Maria drove thought-leadership platforms and influencer programs for a range of multinational clients, including Philips. She also guided clients on proactive gender pay gap positioning and messaging, authored reports, blogs and OpEds, and organized live social media events.
Maria is an advocate of diversity and inclusion and contributed to a D&I thought leadership study launched at WEF 2020. 
Maria has a master’s in international relations from the University of Warwick in the UK, a master's in Journalism from the DePaul University in Chicago, and a diploma in forced migration from Oxford University.

I have always been passionate about applying mathematical reasoning to real-world problems; that is why I decided to do my Undergraduate in Actuarial Sciences, where I developed my statistical, analytical, and programming skills. Afterward, I supported the establishment of a representative office of a reinsurance company in Mexico City and gave international actuarial support.
However, my desire to learn how to obtain, process, and build models out of data made me realize that I want to focus my career in data analytics. Taking this new path will let me continue to grow not only my technical skills but my interpersonal ones and be able to contribute to any industry.
I finished my Master of Data Analytics at Western Ontario in August 2020. Currently, I am working as a Data Scientist at Scotiabank where my day to day activities involve extract data from the Unix servers and analyze the lending products using a customer level approach. As a result, I found myself even further drawn to use my potential to help organizations identify, attract, and retain the most profitable customers and turn their data into business insights for decision making.
